The environmental conditions (like humidity and temperature) also have great influence on LFPs identification [50]. Thus, it is necessary to study the LFPs identification ability of OSiCDs microspheres under different aging conditions. The LFPs remained on the glass for 1, 7, and 14 days in a ventilated room temperature environment, respectively, and then developed with OSiCDs microspheres. The photos clearly show that most of the potential fingerprints can be detected, but the visual resolution decreases as aging time increases (Fig. 7
                     ). There are two main reasons for this phenomenon. On the one hand, the moisture and grease in the residue of the LFPs continue to evaporate, thereby reducing the affinity with OSiCDs microspheres powders [51,52]. On the other hand, a large amount of dust in the air pollutes the surface of LFPs. Furthermore, for the LFPs at higher temperature, the secretion with high volatility degrades rapidly, the content of unsaturated fatty acids decreases significantly, and some amino acids also decompose [53]. Therefore, it is valuable to explore the development effect of OSiCDs microspheres on LFPs aged at a relatively higher temperature. Surprisingly, thanks to the contrast of the fingerprint pattern enhanced by the fluorescent of OSiCDs microspheres, the fingerprint identified on glass plate with LFPs can still obtain level 1–3 features after 30 days in an 80 °C oven (Fig. 8
                     ).
